###i###########################How to Upgrade from RHEL 7 to RHEL 8#############################################
1.Make sure you are using RHEL 7.6 version, if youâ€™re using RHEL version older than RHEL 7.6, you need to update your RHEL system to RHEL 7.6 version using following

# yum update

2. Make sure your RHEL 7 system has the Red Hat Enterprise Linux Server subscription 

# subscription-manager register
# subscription-manager attach --auto
# subscription-manager list --installed

3. Update all software packages to the latest version and reboot the system.

# yum update
# reboot

4. Now set the RHEL 7.9 version as a beginning point for the upgrade using the following command

# subscription-manager release --set 7.9

5. If you have used yum-plugin-versionlock

# yum version lock clear

6. Once system booted, make sure to enable the Extras repository for software package dependencies.

# subscription-manager repos --enable rhel-7-server-extras-rpms
# subscription-manager repos --enable rhel-7-server-rpms

7. Install the Leapp utility.

# yum install leapp

8. Now download additional required data files, which is required by the Leapp utility for a successful upgrade from RHEL 7 to RHEL 8

# cd /etc/leapp/files/ 
# wget https://access.redhat.com/sites/default/files/attachments/leapp-data3.tar.gz
# tar -xf leapp-data3.tar.gz 
# rm leapp-data3.tar.gz

10. Now start the RHEL 7 system upgrade process using the following command.

# leapp answer --section remove_pam_pkcs11_module_check.confirm=True
# leapp upgrade

11. Once upgrades finish, manually reboot the system.

# reboot

12. Now Log in to the RHEL 8 system and change the SELinux mode to enforcing.

# setenforce 1

13. Enable the firewall.

# systemctl start firewalld
# systemctl enable firewalld
# dnf clean packages
#########################################################################################3
Reference
// wget https://access.redhat.com/sites/default/files/attachments/leapp-data8.tar.gz
// https://www.tecmint.com/upgrade-from-rhel-7-to-rhel-8/
// https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4nG2X_pmxv4
############################################################################################
You can run the leapp preupgrade -h command to view the supported target versions.


